# Privacy & Security Standards

## PII Encryption

- All PII encrypted at rest using Fernet symmetric encryption
- Key: `PII_ENCRYPTION_KEY` env var (32-byte base64-encoded)
- Never log, serialize, or expose decrypted PII in API error responses
- PII scrub filter active on all log handlers

## Consent Gate

`ConsentGateMiddleware` blocks PII-accessing endpoints until user gives consent.

- Consent version tracked in `PALP_PRIVACY.CONSENT_VERSION`
- Consent timestamps recorded per-user
- Must check consent before processing any personal data

## Audit Logging

`AuditMiddleware` logs access to sensitive paths defined in `AUDIT_SENSITIVE_PREFIXES`:

```python
AUDIT_SENSITIVE_PREFIXES = [
    "/api/auth/profile/",
    "/api/dashboard/",
    "/api/analytics/",
    "/api/assessment/profile/",
    "/api/adaptive/student/",
    "/api/events/student/",
    "/api/auth/classes/",
    "/api/auth/export/",
]
```

When adding new endpoints that access PII, add the path prefix to this list.

## RBAC Rules

- Student: can only access own data (mastery, pathway, submissions, events)
- Lecturer: can only access data from assigned classes (`LecturerClassAssignment`)
- Admin: full access, manages users and system config
- Cross-user data access = P0 security bug

```python
def get_queryset(self):
    if self.request.user.role == User.Role.STUDENT:
        return Model.objects.filter(student=self.request.user)
    elif self.request.user.role == User.Role.LECTURER:
        return Model.objects.filter(
            student__classmembership__student_class__lecturerassignment__lecturer=self.request.user
        )
```

## Privacy Operations

- Export: user can request full data export (Celery task)
- Deletion: user can request data deletion with retention policy
- Retention enforcement: `privacy.enforce_retention` runs nightly via Celery beat
- Incident SLA: 48 hours (`PALP_PRIVACY.SLA_HOURS`), checked hourly

## Security Checklist (15 items)

When modifying auth/privacy code, verify:
1. PII encrypted at rest
2. TLS enforced (prod)
3. JWT in httpOnly cookies only, not in URL/localStorage
4. RBAC matrix correct for new endpoints
5. No SQL injection vectors (use ORM, never raw SQL with user input)
6. XSS prevention (CSP headers configured in Next.js)
7. CSRF protection active
8. Rate limiting on auth endpoints
9. Error responses don't leak internals
10. Dependencies scanned (Bandit in CI)
11. No secrets in repository
12. Audit trail for sensitive access
13. CORS restricted (`CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGINS`)
14. `DEBUG=False` in production
15. Consent checked before PII access
